  <tr>
   <td colspan="4" class="content">
    <pre>The bug importer uses the python module logging to output messages and errors.
At present this only outputs to stderr, which is fine if your terminal holds
over 20,000 lines of scrollback. Since this is not the case for most people, and
so that people who are not paulproteus can see the error log for the main site,
we need to get these published to the web.

First thing that we need to do is get logging configured properly. Since it is
used sitewide as far as I know, we may as well do this properly. I envisage
(after a five-minute browse of the Python library page for logging) that we have
our own custom logging modules that we import e.g. mysite.logging.customs or
something, that handle the different types of logs that we use/need/want over
the site. Each of these would handle a particular configuration of the logging
module.

Second, we need some way of displaying them. There is probably some nice Django
wizadry that can help here, but not being experienced in Django I will leave
this part for someone else to flesh out =)

Of course, most of the above is only really needed if there are multiple
sections of the site that have logging - if customs is the only log that needs
publishing it could be much simpler. Since I have only worked so far on the bug
importer, I have absolutely no idea what other areas are doing =D Quyite a few
questions depend on the scale of logging needed e.g. do we store logs in flat
files or a database, and how far back do we keep logs.

(Nearly all of the above is likely rambling on my part and may or may not read
well, since the input box for creating the issue in Roundup is too small for me
to read my entire message at once; feel free to make suggestions!)</pre>
   </td>
  </tr>
 
